{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# ACLI subprocess 429 handling: honor Retry-After if available, else jittered backoff\n\n## Context / corrected premise\nAll ACLI calls go through the `_run_acli` subprocess (`acli_subprocess.py`), which sees only returncode + text\nstdout/stderr. The existing `_call_with_backoff` (`acli_subprocess.py:236-292`) ALREADY reads `exc.headers` /\ndoes exponential backoff at ~line 267 for the REST-style path; the plain subprocess retry path does uniform\n2s/4s backoff for ALL non-zero exit codes (except 401/assignee). So `Retry-After` availability on the pure\nsubprocess path is UNVERIFIED and must be proven before it is relied on.\n\n## What / files (`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/acli_subprocess.py`)\n1. PROBE FIRST (spike): run `acli jira workitem search` against a rate-limited/staged endpoint (needs\n   JIRA_URL/JIRA_USER/JIRA_API_TOKEN in env) and record BOTH (a) whether ACLI surfaces `Retry-After` in parseable\n   stderr, AND (b) what EXIT CODE ACLI returns on an HTTP 429 (it is NOT assumed to be 429 — `_run_acli` today only\n   special-cases 401). Record findings on this ticket.\n2. If ACLI surfaces Retry-After: extract via regex from stderr (`Retry-After:\\s*(\\d+)`) and honor it. If not:\n   honor 429 with jittered exponential backoff WITHOUT Retry-After; document it as unavailable on the subprocess\n   path (behavior parity, not mechanism parity, with the REST-style `_call_with_backoff`).\n3. Retryable-code change is EXPLICIT: today the subprocess path retries all non-zero exit codes (except 401/assignee).\n   Decide + document: ADD selective 429/502/503 Retry-After/backoff ON TOP (recommended) vs NARROW to {429,502,503}\n   (a behavior change requiring its own test) — do not silently narrow.\n4. PRESERVE the non-idempotent-write guard (`AcliTimeoutError` is not a `TimeoutError`).\n5. Observability: log when rate-limiting is detected, when backoff triggers, and whether Retry-After was honored or unavailable.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Probe result recorded: whether ACLI surfaces Retry-After on 429 AND the exit code it returns on 429.\n- [ ] 429 backs off with jittered exponential backoff; honors Retry-After IFF the probe confirmed availability.\n- [ ] Retryable-code change explicit + documented (add-on vs narrow); if narrowed, a test covers the changed non-429 exit-code behavior.\n- [ ] Non-idempotent-write no-blind-retry guard preserved; add a case to the EXISTING `tests/.../test_acli_subprocess_timeout.py` (do not invent a new test name).\n- [ ] Rate-limit/backoff/Retry-After events are logged.\n- [ ] The retry/backoff decision is captured in an ADR or the reconciler design doc.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783476728451991001,"uuid":"2aa01aed-8044-48e7-8255-2427c4bc3913"}